{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516007"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12542"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12542"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.25,0.12,0.15,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5041"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5041"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12542"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3803"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15552"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34707"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of fatigue, nausea, vomiting, and low blood pressure. She has a history of rheumatoid arthritis, for which she has been taking steroids for four months while starting methotrexate. She reports missing several doses of her steroids recently due to an intercurrent viral illness. Her other medical history includes type 2 diabetes managed with metformin and regular vitamin B12 injections. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and weak. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate is 16/min, SpO2 is 98% on room air, and temperature is 36.7\u00b0C. There are no other relevant findings on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium: 133 mmol/L (137\u2013145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 4.5 mmol/L (3.5\u20134.9).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to perform prior to initiating management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plasma aldosterone measurement","Short Synacthen test","8 am cortisol level","24-hour urinary free cortisol","No further investigations are required"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman presents with acute symptoms of adrenal insufficiency following recent cessation of long-term steroid therapy. The history of steroid use, abrupt cessation, and the presence of hypotension and hyponatraemia are highly suggestive of secondary adrenal insufficiency due to hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis suppression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further investigations are required\u003C/strong\u003E before management is commenced as the patient is haemodynamically unstable, treatment of the suspected cause must be prioritised. While treatment does delay the capacity for diagnostic testing in adrenal insufficiency, the latter is not the current priority. Expert consensus statements and guidelines emphasise the importance of prompt initiation of treatment in patients with suspected adrenal crisis. Diagnostic investigations should not delay treatment. A blood sample could be drawn immediately for serum cortisol and adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) if suspected, but treatment should be started without waiting for assay results. In an acutely unwell patient, confirmation of diagnosis can be safely established once the patient has clinically recovered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShort Synacthen test\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold-standard diagnostic test for adrenal insufficiency and does help distinguish between primary and secondary adrenal insufficiency when serum ACTH has not been previously assessed. However, its results are inaccurate when the test is performed within 24 hours of steroid dosing. Treatment needs to be prioritised and testing considered later.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E8 am cortisol level\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in the outpatient setting or when the diagnosis is uncertain, but in acute adrenal crisis, results may be misleading and waiting for results could delay life-saving therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary free cortisol\u003C/strong\u003E is used to investigate hypercortisolism, such as in Cushing\u0027s syndrome, and is not appropriate for diagnosing adrenal insufficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma aldosterone measurement\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in the evaluation of primary adrenal insufficiency or disorders of aldosterone production, but not in secondary adrenal insufficiency, where aldosterone production is typically preserved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In a person with suspected secondary adrenal insufficiency due to recent cessation of long-term steroids, immediate empirical steroid replacement is indicated without delay for further investigations.","A short Synacthen (adrenocorticotropic hormone stimulation) test is the gold-standard test for diagnosing adrenal insufficiency but is not appropriate to perform acutely in a deteriorating patient when empiric treatment needs to be prioritised.","24-hour urinary free cortisol and plasma aldosterone are not appropriate for diagnosing acute adrenal insufficiency."],"references":["Endocrine Society Australia. Harmonisation of Endocrine Dynamic Testing (HEDTA). [cited on the 24th of May 2024] Available at: https://www.endocrinesociety.org.au/guidelines.asp","Shaikh S, Nagendra L, Shaikh S, Pappachan JM. Adrenal Failure: An Evidence-Based Diagnostic Approach. Diagnostics (Basel). 2023 May 21;13(10):1812. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics13101812. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37238296/","Borresen SW, Klose M, Glintborg D, Watt T, Andersen MS, Feldt-Rasmussen U. Approach to the Patient With Glucocorticoid-induced Adrenal Insufficiency. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2022 Jun 16;107(7):2065-2076. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35302603/","Dineen R, Thompson CJ, Sherlock M. Adrenal crisis: prevention and management in adult patients. Ther Adv Endocrinol Metab. 2019 Jun 13;10:2042018819848218. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6566489/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12542"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90590"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T